<br>
Isolationist policy is extremely bad.  History has proven the errors of an isolationist policy.   HOWEVER, i think that we as a nation do tend to stick our noses in other peoples business just a bit to damn often.  Isolation only puts blinders on a nations eyes as to the threats that are out there.  I also believe that as a nation we cannot ever be a neutral power either.  We are the most advanced military power left in the world today.<br>
<br>
I am an extreme patriot and believe in our way of life in america and am willing to fight and die for it BUT i am not of the belief that my beliefs are for everyone nor should i enforce my beliefs on another person or nation. (see religion in this aspect as well)<br>
<br>
HOWEVER! (damn im full of contradictions today eh?)  I absolutely believe in the need to remove Saddam from power.  Regardless of my personal beliefs lets look at the facts....<br>
<br>
Saddam is likened to Hitler in his efforts to enforce his rule on his people and kill off opposing factions.  See Kurds and Shi&quot;ite muslims genocide efforts against them in direct violation of UNSCR (United Nations Security Council Resolution) 688 which is where the no-fly zones and no troop buildup zones (UNSCR 949) came from which he has violated over 70+ times since 1991<br>
<br>
Saddam has weapons of mass destruction against the UN resolutions and refuses to destroy said rockets and chemicals etc. per the terms of the 1991 UN resolutions and multiple following UN resolutions. (primarily UNSCR 687)<br>
<br>
He has consistently blocked attempts by UN inspectors  to do their jobs and hidden (apparent) stockpiles of Nuclear, Biological and Chemical war items.<br>
<br>
I could go on and on at how he has consistantly terrorized his own popluation and incidents at which he has clearly violated UN resolutions and picked the US out as a bad guy but we are part of the UN and it is our obligation to meet those resolutions.  I could point out how he has targeted our aircraft in clear violation of resolutions and which are considered hostile acts but i dont believe that is necessary either.<br>
<br>
I do not necessarily believe that it is our job to go over there and take things into our own hands.  But i believe the justification is definitely there.  HOWEVER, i think that before any concrete action is taken we damn well better have a plan of action to take care of the Iraqi people and the region in general if we do go in and take Iraq and that plan better take into account their cultural, religious and other needs that may not necessarily (sp) be immediately apparent.  Forcing our way of life on their population is a bad idea in my not so humble opinion.  <br>
<br>
Will i go over there and die if necessary. Yep, thats what i signed on the dotted line and swore an oath to do.  Its my job.  I do think that people need to look at the bigger picture and be better informed about what is going on around them rather and just spew catchphrases like &quot;kill em all&quot; or &quot;make love not war&quot; more often than not there are varying areas of black/white and gray.  <br>
<br>
Like my opinions or not really doesn't matter to me.  The only thing i wish is that people would do their research before spewing out catchphrases or making unilateral opinions.  All for now.<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub83.ezboard.com/bascension10244.showUserPublicProfile?gid=everas>Everas</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>AD's Iksar Monk_0354</span><br>  Posts: 59<br> <font color=#333333>(2/28/03 9:58 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: hrm</span><hr size=1> Thus far the only things hes had that are in violation were those rockets that exceeded the maximum range the UN imposed. He's agreed to destroy them, albeit not immediately but he has. <br>
<br>
And the popular conclusion that because we haven't managed to find any other weapon's in violation he must be hiding them is kind of absurd. I don't believe for a minute the Bush administration has anything more concrete than we've already seen. If they did there's no possible benefit to concealing that information.<br>
<br>
Furthermore, going to war with someone because we THINK they're violating a disarmament treaty is a horrible idea. Going to war in general is a bad idea, as fun as it might be to bash the French they were right about noone winning.<br>
<br>
The comparison of Saddam to Hitler's alittle weak. Hes certainly brutal, but he doesn't command nearly the power Hitler did. And some of those groups he's decimated aren't exactly peace loving themselves... not that I'm condoning it, its just not a completely black and white situation.<br>
<br>
And when did we become the beakon of morality on earth anyways? Genacide isn't a crime our own country can claim to be innocent of. Even recently we had no problem turning our back on people like Saddam as long as he did what we told him to. No matter how many of their own people they might butcher.<br>
<br>
That said I certainly don't think we should turn our back on Saddam. While I'm not convinced he's the threat Bush claims he is... not by a long shot, I do think the UN should continue monitoring him. And if they find he's in violation, and if he refuses to comply, then and only then should we take action against him WITH the UN.<br>
<br>
Tired of watching our officials use our nation like their own personal chessboard. Our foreign policy has been attrocious since the end of WW2. And all those poor decisions our leaders made are coming back to haunt us. It'd be nice if we'd learn from our past mistakes and not keep adding to them. <br>
<br>
I'm sure I'm not the only one thats heard over and over again how we police the globe. For or against that policy though, we've done a really shitty job of it. We abuse weaker countries for our own benefit all the time by supporting people just like Saddam. When that fails to get us what we want, we invade... is it any wonder people hate us? <br>
<br>
I don't imagine any of us would appreciate it if a foreign power invaded our country and told us what kind of government we'd have and who would run it. Foolish idea right? Well, we'll see. If there's one thing we should learn from history, it's noone stays on top forever.<br>
<br>
-Ebon <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub83.ezboard.com/bascension10244.showUserPublicProfile?gid=taranna>Taranna</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>HiElf Snob</span><br>  Posts: 565<br> <font color=#333333>(2/28/03 11:07 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: hrm</span><hr size=1> I voted no and no on the poll- my reasoning follows and is somewhat lengthy and opinionated.  It is rather long, don't read it if you don't want to :P<br>
<br>
Suprising that the justification for war has shifted somewhat, from WMD to the so-called &quot;moral case&quot; for regime change.  Or perhaps not so suprising, given the desperate paucity of evidence of Iraq being a serious threat to western interests.  Following are the Bush quotes from the poll thread and my opinions on them.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>&quot;Success in Iraq could begin a new stage for Middle Eastern peace, and set in motion progress towards a truly democratic Palestinian state&quot;<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
The two situations have nothing whatever to do with one another.  Progress towards a democratic Palestinian state does not hinge on removing a secular dictator in a neighbouring country, nor would it affect it in any positive fashion.  The US/UK are not seen as impartial arbiters in the region, particularly the US for its unilateral support of Israel, itself a flagrant violater of UN resolutions regarding the illegal occupation of large portions of land belonging to neighbouring countries.  Not to mention breach of pre-1967 borders.  <br>
<br>
No, the only realistic way to resolve this crisis is with a broad-based multilateral approach that will be seen by <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>both</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> sides as impartial.  That was the strength of the Oslo accord- multilateral support from an unbiased standpoint.  The first goal in this must surely be the establishment of credible political institutions.  Executive, Legislative and Judicial- the three arms of future Palestinian government need to be established and proven effective in say, a 6 month test case.  <br>
<br>
This is eminently achievable- the current Israeli government quite naturally doesn't desire it- they would have withdrawn to pre-1967 borders if they did.  Neither do the Palestinian side desire this to any great extent- mob rule through the laughable PA funds Fatah, Al-Aqsa and helps arm them.  Much in the same way the US arms the state of Israel- quietly as possible, but in the public domain.  It therefore behoves this multilateral comittee to treat both sides equally- forgiving neither of them for agreement infractions.  This is all academic though, until the institutions are set up properly.  A war in Iraq <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>will not create these institutions</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  In fact, given how much moderate Arab opinion would be alienated in the event of an attack, it would likely make the task even more difficult.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>&quot;The passing of Saddam Hussein's regime will deprive terrorist networks of a wealthy patron that pays for terrorist training<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
If I wanted to be cynical, the CIA during the 1980s could easily have been described as a wealthy patron of Osama Bin Laden, Mohammed Kaif, Zaheer Musharra Mohammed and other prominent terrorist figures in the world today, one that paid for their training.  Back then they were considered key allies (terrorist allies, but against a bellicose Soviet army you'd take anything I suppose).  But I live in the real world- and if the official line is that distasteful alliances of convenience are the practiced norm...fine- I'll accept that with a heavy heart.  What I won't put up with is the idea that Bush *or* my prime minister are in possession of the moral high ground.  They've both claimed it- but given policies they and their parties have backed to the hilt in days gone by, I find it suprising that they would even try.  <br>
<br>
To the actual point of the quote- the only terrorists that exist in Iraq are in the practically autonomous Kurdistan in the north- a region of the country the Iraqi regime has no control over.  In fact, it's the presence of such terrorist training camps and claims of Kurdish autonomy that has prompted Saddam to bomb and gas them at every opportunity.  Ironically enough- if it was the intention of either my prime minister Tony Blair or George Bush to *support* Saddam's inhuman acts- they would be saying he is <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>fighting</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> terrorism rather than supporting it.  They're already doing this elsewhere- Russian soldiers firing napalm rockets into densely populated cities in Chechnya is &quot;fighting terrorism&quot; when it suits the US/UK administrations.  Israeli tanks bulldozing entire residential areas in the West Bank is considered &quot;fighting terrorism&quot;, and a regime's soldiers fatally shooting teenage boys throwing stones is considered &quot;a fair and measured response&quot; by our respective governments (I have yet to hear tell of a soldier seriously wounded or killed by a teenage boy throwing a small rock).  There is no clear moral consistency of policy, our governments should not even pretend that one exists.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>and offers rewards to families of suicide bombers. And other regimes will be given a clear warning that support for terror will not be tolerated.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Oh, the irony.  Numerous institutions and sources in the US for decades financed rewards to Republican and Loyalist families alike in Northern Ireland, supporting the families of terrorists that have killed tens of thousands of British citizens over decades. US administrations over 50 years have failed to consider it a threat or a grave insult.  How opinions change- Americans donating money to terrorist families in Northern Ireland is a tolerable evil, Saddam tolerating Iraqis doing the same to families of suicide bombers isn't however.  For the record, I'm against the idea of rewarding terrorism in any shape or form- but punish thousands of innocent civilians for the actions of a government they didn't choose?  Especially when you as a government tolerate the same at home and elsewhere.  That's a bit of a stretch for the old moral case for war if ever I saw one.<br>
<br>
As for a warning to other regimes about &quot;terrorism not being tolerated&quot;- that's laughable to be honest.  The vast majority of those 11/9 hijackers were Saudi, not Iraqi- America's most important Arab ally in the Middle East is arguably Saudi Arabia.  The largest source of funding for Palestinian terror groups emanates from Saudi Arabia and Kuwait- supposedly our most important allies in the region.  Last year alone, September 15, 2002 the UK and US governments in a joint deal approved millions of dollars of credit to these governments, who have tolerated the funding of terrorist groups since the late 1960's- way to send the message to terrorist-supporting countries.  A terrible and disgraceful insult to the memory of those thousands of innocents brutally murdered in New York.  The message will never be sent, because to be perfectly honest- our governments need their oil and friendly relationship more than they need to tackle terrorist support seriously in those countries.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>&quot;A new regime in Iraq would serve as a dramatic and inspiring example of freedom for other nations in the region.&quot;<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I'm still holding my breath- Egypt, Turkey and Jordan don't seem to have influenced their neighbours' modes of government terribly effectively.  If anything it's isolated them within the Arab league.  Besides- since when was democracy something you could impose externally?  It's been tried in Afghanistan, with terrible results.  80% of their country is unrepresented, warlords roam around with fistfuls of dollars and minature armies of former Northern Alliance troops carving out their own areas of dominance.  Iraq's population is even more starkly divided ethnically- imposed democracy is an unachievable myth.  It has to be built from the ground up- a US/British military protectorate government isn't the way to do that.  <br>
<br>
I find it immoral and utterly repugnant that we're rushing into a course of action that threatens so many lives, and has given little or no thought (I suspect the latter) to the post-war scenario.  I may not agree with you whether or not there is moral justification for the war Walks- but I agree 100% that in the event of one, there needs to be a plan for institutions.  The current one is a panel of US/UK generals with totalitarian control over Iraqi administrative organs and national resources.  The US and UK <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>badly</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> need credibility in the Middle East, and that can only be achieved by acting in a fair and morally correct manner- that isn't either.<br>
<br>
The moral high ground lies in a peaceful resolution of the crisis and placing faith in inspections.  The results are there for all to see.  95% of WMD destroyed so far in Iraq have been destroyed by inspection teams over 5 years, a mere 5% destroyed by the combined might of US/UK/French forces in 1991 and intelligence/air operations since.  Inspections <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>work</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, if they're given the time and space to do their job.  Whether they have that or not, only they know.  The last regime of inspections went on for five years and destroyed significant quantities of these weapons.  I find it absurd that some nations at the UNSC want to terminate inspections after 11 weeks.  If Hans Blix and El-Baradei come to the UNSC and say &quot;Sorry, we're unable to do our work, there is just no way inspections can continue&quot;- then the peaceful avenue has been exhausted, and there is a moral and practical case for comitting forces.  Furthermore, if the inspectors say they can't do their job, no one will support military action more strongly than I.  Currently, neither of these is true- inspectors, the people on the ground, the experts, still believe it worthwhile to continue inspections.  I'm no expert on arms or diplomacy, but politicians aren't either- they should take expert advice when required, some of them are ignoring it or spinning it in favour of national interest.  I believe their motives for doing this are selfish, irresponsible and a textbook example of leadership decisions based in fear rather than strength of conviction. <br>
<br>
Just a brief glance at history shows that any imposed government or system of government in the Middle East has failed, both in the country it's tried in, and in its efforts to influence neighbours.  The US-imposed totalitarian Shah of Iran didn't encourage &quot;democracy&quot; in his neighbours any more than the Soviet puppet government in Yemen spread the word of the Communist party politik in <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>its</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> neighbours.  I use democracy in inverted commas because as I said, an externally imposed system of government is in contravention of the very basic principles of democracy.  Dictators and totalitarian undemocratic states have always been surrounded by democratic states throughout history, that has never influenced their policies.  I don't see Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, Bahrain, Oman, Syria or Yemen abandoning their systems of government just because we effect regime change in Iraq- putting that forward as a possibility is naive and shows little appreciation of the history of such changes.<br>
<br>
To conclude- several thousand of our troops and American troops are as I type this, preparing to risk their lives in doing their duty.  I wish them the very best of luck, and a safe journey home to their families, it's the least they deserve.  They only await instruction from their political masters.  I long to live in a world where those politicians so ready to risk others' lives on the behalf of morally bankrupt policy listen to <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>their</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> masters the electorate.  In the absence of that, democracy has failed, and it is innocent Iraqi people and the people of the region who will pay the ultimate price as a result.<br>
<br>
 <p>Taranna Dhossarim<br>
