<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>bush wasnt unable.... he was unwilling.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Wrong I'm afraid- I think he would have liked nothing better than to &quot;finish the job&quot; from his point of view.  He was unable- because of diplomatic commitments in the region and the fragility of the arab coalition he'd built to actually effect a regime change.  And that was for the better to be honest...anyone remember the last time there was a US-sponsored regime change in the region?  Didn't end too well as I recall, we're still living with the consequences of that, as are the people of Iran, trying to throw of the shackles of a past blighted by US foreign policy.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>to have removed saddam at that time would have cuased a power vaccum and led to even more chaos in the region<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
And what do you think would happen if there was a regime change now Somthor?  That's what is being discussed- and what I suspect men like Donald Rumsfeld, Paul Wolfowitz and Dick Cheyney have wanted since 1991.  Every excuse for going to war has been cynically exploited and manipulated to maximum effect.  These are the men pushing this policy and driving it forward.  They are at the heart of the absurd change in strategy from containment, deterrence and diplomacy to military pre-emption.  <br>
<br>
Let us illustrate it in clearer terms- an accomplished statesman like FDR or Harold Wilson would seek to understand those of a different disposition and engage them.  No matter that they were unsavoury regimes- diplomacy is the art of achieving dialogue irrespective of differences.  By engaging them the hope would be that with deterrence and a policy of external containment they could be reasoned with, and change effected over a period of time.  The entire Cold War was managed without either of the principle protagonists firing a shot at each other in anger because of this calm, reasoned and sensible approach.  As a result- the brutal regime that was the Soviet Union came to its knees, not trembling at NATO's military might, but unable to compete in the arena peacefully and on equal footing.  <br>
<br>
Compare this to the policy of pre-emption, exemplified best by an Afghan warlord- say, Rashid Dostam, one of the northern alliance commanders, who in the last coup massacred fifteen thousand POWs in the city of Kandahar as a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>pre-emptive measure</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, lest any of them take arms and rise up against him again.  To make sure, he took the eminently sensible precaution of slaughtering their families too, most of them innocent Pashtun civilians.  I tell you, it brought a nice warm feeling to my heart when I saw him enter the city triumphantly *again*- only this time with full US/UK backing and special forces from our respective countries flanking his motorcade.  Needless to say, he has since been appointed to the makeshift cabinet and is busily arming his troops for his next pre-emptive action, destroying his potential enemies before they have a chance to &quot;threaten him&quot;.  The shocking irony is, that from his bloodthirsty point of view, he can't lose!  Because if they weren't his enemies at all or had no designs on his position...they'd now be forced into being his enemies if they wanted to stay alive.  Now that's the face of pre-emption- it's a mapped guesswork strategy of potential risk, backed up by a complete lack of evidence and reasonably collected intelligence.  Remind you of anything?  :P<br>
<br>
I've been told Sadaam is a threat to me by several people, my government, and one or two other governments.  Well my answer is clear and simple- bloody well prove it.  There might be materials in there that could possibly in theory be cobbled together to make a biological weapon.  Oh and it gets better- no operational missile system in Iraq can reach us.  Ahh, the warmongers say- but with no inspectors in Iraq for 4 years, who knows what he might be hiding.  Does anyone else find that as excrutiatingly paranoid a stance as me?  Whenever I hear that remark on television- the stark suspicion and paranoid delusional allegations in the absence of proof reminds me of McCarthyism.  I mean bloody hell, if someone walked like a communist or ate communist breakfast cereal in America at that time he deserved to be persecuted.  I can't get away from the feeling that I'm witnessing this on an international scale.  And not even on a consistent basis- North Korea has nuclear weapons and has threatened to use them <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>pre-emptively</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  Well gee, wonder who gave them that idea...I think his name is Paul Wolfowitz and it's written down in a strategy document somewhere.  <br>
<br>
No matter, they've got nukes, threatened their neighbours and the entire western world with their use if sanctions are applied- and we want to resolve <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>that</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> diplomatically and do business with the North Koreans.  They are clearly the greater threat- and lean dangerously close towards being a suicidal regime.  <br>
<br>
Sadaam Hussein is definately *not* suicidal- he's a survivor and always has been.  The very idea that even if these alleged weapons were in a useable state that he would fall on his own sword by using them...is so laughable I find myself crying out in despair that some believe that he would.  It'd result in the most devastating retaliatory attack in the history of mankind- the UK *alone* has two (declared) SSBNs armed and deployed- HMS <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Swordfish</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> and HMS <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Marlin</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  These carry enough Trident missile sorties to destroy Iraq, and ALL its neighbours...four times over.  And that's just *our* submarine deployment...the US has four to five times our strength in forces in the region.  The only way anyone but a madman would act with that arrayed against him would be say...if he was invaded and had nothing to lose?  Oh...darn.<br>
<br>
Containment works, deterrence works, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>inspections</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> work.  No other process or system has been as effective in disarming Iraq or any other country- the last war in the Gulf destroyed a fraction of the arsenal, 95% of it was achieved by inspectors.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>lastly get us the hell out of the UN <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
...I don't know whether to laugh or cry after reading that, and the other ludicrous isolationist drivel preceding it.  In case you haven't noticed Somthor- communication and the digital age, amongst other things, mean we live in a shrinking world.  Nation states are tied closer together by trade and cooperation than ever before...and you want to stick your head in the sand?  It's not going to happen...nor should it- that attitude is what caused more and bloodier wars than any other stance (other than pre-emption) in the 20th or any other century.  <br>
<br>
The only way legitimacy can be accrued is with consensus and the international rule of law- the cornerstone of that principle *IS* the United Nations.  With great power comes great responsibility- the responsibility to use that power for the greater good...not to selfishly serve national interest.  During the Cold War, the UNSC was a trading-shop of vetos and botched initiatives, wrangling amongst permanent members.  In the post-cold war world we have a chance to make the international system work...and you want to retreat away from that?  <br>
<br>
That kind of isolationism allows terrorists to thrive and flourish, allows legitimacy to be attached to the brutal and bloody murder of innocents.  What makes your government, my government or *any* government any better than terrorists if they knowingly pursue a conflict which they know full well will kill thousands of innocents people?  If we are to have legitimacy, credibility or a lasting peace- if we want any chance at all of fighting terrorism on all levels and winning- we cannot afford to have governments that think the way you do Somthor.  <br>
<br>
Cooperation and consistency of policy- police, intelligence and political forces of all countries working with trust and understanding- that is the only way to win the fight against terror.  After 11/9, the US and the west in general had more sympathy than ever before from moderate Arab opinion in the middle East.  The Bush administration is about to throw that all away by pushing a war policy against Iraq, alone if need be.  That would alienate the very body of opinion you *have* to win over in order to fight terrorism, to secure the future of Israeli-Palestinian peace, that body of opinion is crucial if democracy is to become an accepted norm in that region.  I ask you this- if America does what you suggest and walks away...what on earth is to stop another terrorist attack?  Go on, tell me how Bali was an important strategic target for terrorists.  Doing nothing is no guarantee of safety- in order to stop terrorism you have to engage the issues that fuel terrorism- surely I can't be the only person on this board who seriously believes that?<br>
<br>
To conclude-  without international consensus based on the rule of law, legitimacy is sacrificed- and there is no case for war.  I do believe in the idea of a moral and just war, when the alternative is a clear, imminent threat that cannot be ignored.  Abandoning that stance, we are left with uncaring hawks, whose only chosen international credibility issues from the barrel of a gun.  Reminds me an awful lot of that chap Rashid Dostam.  I sure as hell don't want to live in a world like that Somthor...would you- would any of us?<br>
<br>
 <p>Taranna Dhossarim<br>
