</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub83.ezboard.com/bascension10244.showUserPublicProfile?gid=taranna>Taranna</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>HiElf Snob</span><br>  Posts: 569<br> <font color=#333333>(3/2/03 9:58 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Bush</span><hr size=1> The objective is not to change peoples' opinions Rurik- I'm not self-indulgent enough to think that for a moment.  The aim rather is to point out the consequences of abandoning long-established forums and ignoring the cornerstones of international law.  I can't think of a single respected expert that doesn't acknowledge the severity of a League of Nations style collapse of the Un caused by a founding permanent member going its own way.  Not everyone is aware of how dangerous an event that such a blatant act- ignoring the UN charter could have on subsequent international events.  Hopefully my posts were somewhat informative and encourage people to read more about the details and history of the crisis at hand.  Let's not kid ourselves here- there is an astonishing level of ignorance of international affairs to be surmounted.  <br>
<br>
Not to mention the seemingly inconceivable notion that to criticize one's leaders is unpatriotic or unseemly at a time of possible war.  This is when we must be <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>most</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> critical of our leaders, not pander to their egos.  When young men and women are preparing to risk their lives for a policy- shouldn't we ask why?  That goes for large sections of the US press and other forms of TV media too incidentally, who I feel have been excessively tolerant of their leaders' actions since 11/9.  It should never be unpatriotic to question the motives of our leaders or criticize a case for war- in the absence of such criticism there is no effective opposition and democracy fails.<br>
<br>
On the point of the link you posted Rurik- I fully understand that Sadaam is an evil dictator, and the Ba'ath party is a repugnant and repressive regime.  However, I put it to you that this has been well-recognized and known by NGOs for over 3 decades- and that during the 1980s this tyrannical regime had no stronger supporter than the United States.  Arms, intelligence, communications equipment and anthrax strains were all liberally shared with this regime- he was given credit to aid in the further development of WMDs as well.  So the idea that human rights are even in the calculations of an administration that includes Donald Rumsfeld, Dick Cheney and Wolfowitz- three men <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>instrumental</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> in supporting Sadaam during the Reagan years- is a preposterous one.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Alot of people in the US (at least where i live, which is a very mixed community) are extremly frustrated with the UN.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
I put it to you that the reason that there is frustration with the UN is that a majority in the UNSC do not support the position of your government.  And what is democracy without a variety of ideas and policies that clash may I ask?  Without effective opposition and a willingness to consult with alternative points of view, democracy is diminished.  I believe it was Sir William Pitt who said &quot;In the absence of a willingness to debate issues openly there is no government that can be trusted fully.  Without clear opposition and robust dialogue, politics is diminished, liberty melts away and we are the poorer as a society.&quot;  Democracy isn't about one clear defined policy that is universally accepted and carried out.  That sounds to me like a dictatorship quite frankly- without an exchange of views and attention to consensus you don't have a democratic system.<br>
<br>
The UN is based on a democratic system- a forum where a frank and open exchange of views results in resolutions which carry legitimacy.  I would like to know how anyone who posts here and opposes the United Nations as a principle...how they would propose to tackle the current crisis.  The UN is seen as impartial- this is crucial for resolving the current crisis.  Individual nations and their selfish actions in national interest will never have as much legitimacy in resolving anything.  Granted there is little altruism in the way the UNSC operates internally- but there is <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>consensus</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> and a reasonably fair division of responsibility.  It still remains the truth, that a combination and compromise of many varying national interests will carry infinitely more credibility than one nation acting alone.<br>
<br>
As for them being unable to decide anything- well that's nonsense quite frankly.  The UNHCR, UNESCO and UNCHR safeguard human rights, the safety of refugees and the rights of children around the world- millions of lives are saved because of their policies.  The WHO has successfully eradicated smallpox as a disease from the planet- point me to a single country on its own that can even come close to doing as much for world health as them.  The UNSC also has a fine record post-Cold War of resolving disputes.  The Balkan crisis was ultimately resolved through UNSC consensus, as was the reconstruction programme that is rebuilding Serbia-Montenegro after Kosovo.  On the issue of disarmament- several former Soviet republics, South Africa, Libya and Syria have all successfully been disarmed by UNSCOM or similar comissions.  We live in a safer world because of the UN- it is the selfish actions of member states and a few in particular...that fuel terrorism and undermine its security.<br>
<br>
I repeat again- the only way in which terrorism can be combated successfully is with international consensus.  Withdrawing from Kyoto, ABM, the UN convention on biological weapons, the ICC, a whole sleugh of other international agreements on the rights of refugees- the Bush administration is threatening that consensus.  There is no legitimacy in backing a unilateral war of aggression against Iraq.  In fact, I have no doubt Al-Qaeda are rubbing their hands with glee at the prospect of a war in Iraq- here's why:<br>
<br>
1)  &quot;We keep faith with god that this infidel will one day be struck down by the fiery sword of vengeance, his people liberated and free to bask in the glory of the true god.  His guns silenced and his punishment on earth secured, the land liberated from an infidel who has defiled it with his godless values.&quot;  <br>
<br>
Yes Osama is a dangerous and evil individual- except in that quote he isn't talking about Bush, wasn't even the US, the UK, or indeed the West.  He is talking about Sadaam Hussein and Iraq.  Al-Qaeda and Sadaam are mortal enemies- they'd like nothing better than to see him deposed.  And it isn't just an ideological benefit- they see a weak unstable Iraq, divided against itself and ruled by a foreign general as ripe pickings for another Taliban-esque friendly regime to hide in.  An islamic extremist state in Iraq is a very real possibility- if we drew lessons from history, we know that a regime change in that region drives the population to extremism.  Just look at Iran after the Shah- did a US-led regime change <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>there</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> result in a stable democratic pro-Western government?  Did it hell.  The entire stability of Middle East governments could easily be threatened by such a war.<br>
<br>
2) That instability is another easy target for Al-Qaeda, a spate of attacks on government targets in these regimes made unstable by a war could easily turn the Middle East into an inferno of religious hatred and a hotbed of fundamentalism.  The very opinion the US had in its pocket after 11/9 will melt away in the wake of unilateral action in Iraq.  That opinion is crucial in any war against terror- if public opinion in those countries is behind your policy then terrorists would be shunned and spurned, they'd have nowhere to hide, no one willing to arm them.  If Israel withdrew to pre-1967 borders and was able to negotiate with a <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>credible</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> Palestinian government(not a collection of mobsters masquerading as one)- if Israel stopped bulldozing palestinian homes...how the devil would Al-Aqsa and Hamas be able to function?<br>
<br>
3)  Last, but not least- a war unsponsoered by the UN would be the best recruiting poster Al-Qaeda ever had.  Unilateral support for Israel, propping up oil rich states while the people in those states suffer- those are harder issues to sell to reasonable people. They are still important issues, one the current US administration has yet to confront.  But a war in Iraq would draw the battle lines far more clearly, and make it far easier for terrorist groups to stir up discontent and hatred for unilateral American action motivated by selfish national interest.  If the action is carried out under the umbrella of the UN- it isn't American aggression but the will of the international community.  See how important UN approval is Somthor?  Legitimacy pulls the rugs out from under the terrorists- unilateral wars of aggression strengthen their case for recruitment.<br>
<br>
Lastly, just to make my stance clear- my argument is not with the people of the US, it is with the right-wing collection of former oil men masquerading as the executive branch of its government.  A government spearheaded by a man who won fewer of your votes than his opponent...and still became President.  11/9 moved me and many others to tears- it'd break my heart if we actually <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>encouraged</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> the terrorists to come at us by pursuing as morally bankrupt and short-sighted a policy as this.  We would almost certainly, the US and the UK win any war in Iraq- but would we win the battle of hearts and minds needed to fight the threat of terrorism?  I very much doubt that we would.<br>
<br>
 <p>Taranna Dhossarim<br>
65 Archon<br>
